x4freetext: For the excitation functions, eight ORTEC
surface barrier detectors were mounted on a
35-cm-diam. ring which fit into the scattering
chamber. This allowed each angle to be set
independently to +-0.1 degree. Solid angles for the
with a traveling microscope to 1% accuracy, were
typically 0.500 msr; the angular acceptance was 0.5
degree. For most of the differential cross-section
used, mounted 30 degrees apart. Circular apertures
gave an angular acceptance of 1.2` and a typical
solid angle of 3.50 +- 0.04 msr. The electronic
equipment was conventional. Since only 4 ABC`s were
available, more than four detectors were accommodated
by routing the ABC output. All of the digitized
signals were fed a CDC 3100 computer, in which a
block of memory was assigned to each detector.
No uncertainties are given in curves. The  statistical
accuracy of the final data varied due to  the rapid
fluctuation of yield with energy and angle;  a cross
section of 10 mb was measured to a  statistical
accuracy of approximately 3%. The  accuracy of the
beam charge measurement was better  than 2%.
